hands_on_practices.problem:
A continuous random variable $X$ is defined over the interval $[0, 1]$. Its probability density function (PDF), denoted by $f(x)$, is given by:

$$
f(x) = \begin{cases}
C(x^a - x^b) & \text{if } 0 \le x \le 1 \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$

For this specific problem, the constants are given as $C=30$, $a=4$, and $b=5$. So the PDF is:

$$
f(x) = \begin{cases}
30(x^4 - x^5) & \text{if } 0 \le x \le 1 \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$

The expected value (or mean) of a continuous random variable $X$, denoted as $E[X]$, is defined as:

$$
E[X] = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} x f(x) \,dx
$$

Derive the expected value, $E[X]$, for the given probability density function.
